sec.p:
Edge Definition: The edges of our graph are constructed to represent the functional connectivity between the pairs of nodes. We quantify this relationship using the Pearson correlation coefficient, a standard measure for assessing the linear relationship between two time series. For any pair of nodes, $i$ and $j$, the weight of the edge $w_{i j}$ is defined as the absolute value of the correlation coefficient between their feature time series, $\mathbf{x}_{i}$ and $\mathbf{x}_{j}$. The absolute value ensures that both positive and negative correlations, which represent shared temporal dynamics, are equally considered based on their strength. The mathematical formulation is as follows:
\begin{equation*}
w_{i j}=\left|\operatorname{corr}\left(\mathbf{x}_{i}, \mathbf{x}_{j}\right)\right\vert=\frac{\left|\sum_{t=1}^{T}\left(x_{i t}-\bar{x}_{i}\right)\left(x_{j t}-\bar{x}_{j}\right)\right\vert}{\sqrt{\sum_{t=1}^{T}\left(x_{i t}-\bar{x}_{i}\right)^{2}} \sqrt{\sum_{t=1}^{T}\left(x_{j t}-\bar{x}_{j}\right)^{2}}}
\end{equation*}
where $x_{i t}$ is the calcium activity of neuron $i$ at time $t$, and $\bar{x}_{i}$ is the mean calcium activity of neuron $i$ over the entire time series of length $T$.

To create a sparse and interpretable graph, we employ a thresholding procedure. An edge is established between neuron $i$ and neuron $j$ only if their calculated correlation coefficient $w_{i j}$ exceeds a predefined threshold $\theta$. This process effectively filters out weak, potentially spurious correlations, thereby highlighting the most salient functional connections and reducing the computational complexity for subsequent GNN layers. The resulting weighted adjacency matrix $\mathbf{A} \in \mathbb{R}^{N \times N}$ is defined as:
\begin{equation*}
A_{i j}= \begin{cases}w_{i j}, & \text { if } w_{i j} \geq \theta \\ 0, & \text { otherwise }\end{cases}
\end{equation*}

The initial layer is a GCN [12], which aggregates features from a node's immediate neighborhood. This layer's operation is defined as:
\begin{equation*}
\mathbf{H}^{(l+1)}=\sigma\left(\hat{\mathbf{D}}^{-\frac{1}{2}} \hat{\mathbf{A}} \hat{\mathbf{D}}^{-\frac{1}{2}} \mathbf{H}^{(l)} \mathbf{W}^{(l)}\right)
\end{equation*}
where $\hat{\mathbf{A}}=\mathbf{A}+\mathbf{I}$ (the adjacency matrix with self-loops), $\hat{\mathbf{D}}$ is the degree matrix of $\hat{\mathbf{A}}, \mathbf{W}^{(l)}$ is a learnable weight matrix, and $\sigma(\cdot)$ is a non-linear activation function, such as ReLU. This layer effectively captures local dependencies and learns an initial embedding of the neuronal population's topology.

Following the GCN, we employ a GraphSAGE [13] layer to broaden the receptive field and aggregate features from a wider, sampled neighborhood. This layer enhances the model's ability to learn robust feature representations. The aggregation rule for a node $v_{i}$ is given by:
\begin{equation*}
\mathbf{h}_{i}^{(l+1)}=\sigma\left(\mathbf{W}_{1}^{(l)} \cdot \mathbf{h}_{i}^{(l)}+\mathbf{W}_{2}^{(l)} \cdot \operatorname{AGG}\left(\left\{\mathbf{h}_{j}^{(l)}, \forall j \in \mathcal{N}(i)\right\}\right)\right)
\end{equation*}

The final GNN layer is a GAT [14], which introduces an attention mechanism to assign different weights to neighboring nodes, highlighting their varying importance. The attention coefficients $e_{i j}$ between node $i$ and neighbor $j$ are calculated as:
\begin{equation*}
e_{i j}=\operatorname{LeakyReLU}\left(\mathbf{a}^{T}\left[\mathbf{W} \mathbf{h}_{i} \vert \mathbf{W} \mathbf{h}_{j}\right]\right)
\end{equation*}
where $\mathbf{a}$ and $\mathbf{W}$ are learnable parameters. The attention weights $\alpha_{i j}$ are then normalized using the softmax function:
\begin{equation*}
\alpha_{i j}=\operatorname{softmax}\left(e_{i j}\right)=\frac{\exp \left(e_{i j}\right)}{\sum_{k \in \mathcal{N}(i)} \exp \left(e_{i k}\right)}
\end{equation*}

The new feature representation for node $i$ is a weighted sum of its neighbors' features:
\begin{equation*}
\mathbf{h}_{i}^{\prime}=\sigma\left(\sum_{j \in \mathcal{N}(i)} \alpha_{i j} \mathbf{W} \mathbf{h}_{j}\right)
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

The complete model architecture (as shown in Figure 2) feeds the graph information, aggregated through the multilayer GNN, into a Multi-Layer Perceptron (MLP) classifier. A readout function aggregates the final node features from the last GNN layer into a single graph-level representation, $\mathbf{h}_{\text {graph }}$, which is then input to the MLP:
\begin{equation*}
\mathbf{h}_{\text {graph }}=\operatorname{READOUT}\left(\left\{\mathbf{h}_{i}^{(L)}, \forall i \in V\right\}\right)
\end{equation*}

The MLP classifier maps this representation to the final predicted behavioral states, leveraging the most discriminative features learned from the multi-modal data to achieve highprecision behavioral prediction.
\begin{equation*}
\mathbf{y}_{\text {pred }}=\operatorname{softmax}\left(\operatorname{MLP}\left(\mathbf{h}_{\text {graph }}\right)\right)
\end{equation*}

